# Day 5 - Apex Introduction

## 1. What is Apex?

Apex is a strongly typed, object-oriented programming language developed by Salesforce. It is used to execute flow and transaction control statements on the Salesforce platform. Apex allows developers to add custom business logic to Salesforce applications when declarative tools such as Flows and Validation Rules are not sufficient.

### Key Features of Apex

* Runs on Salesforce servers.
* Similar syntax to Java and C#.
* Supports object-oriented programming concepts.
* Can interact with Salesforce database using SOQL and SOSL.
* Used for Triggers, Classes, Batch Jobs, REST APIs, and Integrations.

---

## 2. Difference Between Flow vs Apex

| Feature             | Flow                       | Apex                     |
| ------------------- | -------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| Type                | Declarative Tool           | Programming Language     |
| Development         | Drag-and-drop              | Code-based               |
| Complexity          | Simple to Medium           | Medium to Complex        |
| Maintenance         | Easier                     | Requires coding skills   |
| Performance         | Good for simple automation | Better for complex logic |
| Reusability         | Limited                    | Highly reusable          |
| Integration Support | Basic                      | Advanced                 |

### Configuration vs Coding

| Configuration                                   | Coding                                 |
| ----------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| No-code/Low-code approach                       | Requires programming                   |
| Faster development                              | More development time                  |
| Easier for administrators                       | Requires developers                    |
| Best for standard business processes            | Best for custom requirements           |
| Examples: Flows, Validation Rules, Page Layouts | Examples: Apex Classes, Triggers, APIs |

---

## 3. Real Examples Where Apex Is Needed

### Example 1: Student Scholarship Eligibility

A university wants to automatically calculate scholarship eligibility based on attendance, GPA, extracurricular activities, and family income. Since multiple conditions and calculations are involved, Apex is required.

### Example 2: External Payment Gateway Integration

When students pay fees online, Salesforce must communicate with an external payment system through APIs. Apex is used to send and receive data securely.

### Example 3: Automatic Seat Allocation

When admission applications exceed available seats, Apex can implement a ranking algorithm to allocate seats based on merit scores and reservation categories.

